HS holds $10m reserve cash.

But crucially if 1 in 45 projects is an early success all other projects benefit, as the HS equity rises and thus the value of the tokens will rise, meaning the other projects benefit from their funding tokens rising in value as their cohorts succeed.

This motivates the community to help each other succeed. The community will coalesce around whichever project is making the most valuable progress at any given time. 

Its market driven labour allocation within a community.  Lots of interesting dynamics flow from this structure. Such as projects wanting to self select strong cohort members.

Approval could be democratic with an application entry of 500 projects, and the top 45 being approved. All projects would want to be in HS with other successful projects. Their funding grows with any community success.

Lots of creases to iron out, but an interesting model for web3 funding

I missed most of the call, but wanted to leave some thoughts. I think it's a great program, but needs a bit more organization and clarity. All of the branches you mentioned (investing, contributions, etc) are very meshed together and indistinguishable to new members. My suggestion is to increase contrast between these branches everywhere: specific categories in the Discord, distinction on the website (through subdomains), and in marketing. Since there isn't much marketing material yet, an introduction/product-directory in "onboarding" would help new members understand how Hyperscale is structured.

If you look at examples of other branched organizations, like Fiverr (selling/buying) or WealthSimple (trade/cash/taxes), each of these companies have clear paths from onboarding (marketing or landing page) to their destination (whatever branch they're interested in). Hyperscale could even combine these in marketing to be interpreted as one package, like Fiverr does, but the UX paths need to be clear.

Overall, it seems to have a lot of potential. I applied for funding, but I'm also interested in helping others here. With a bit more organization and clarity, this could work incredibly well. Also, kudos to the design team on the website, it looks amazing.
